fields: Unstable aircraft equilibrium {{c1::diverges from::diverges or approaches}} the equilibrium position after a disturbance
If aircraft equilibrium is {{c1::neutrally stable}}, then after a disturbance, the disturbance stays present, but does not increase.
If an equilibrium is {{c1::stable}}, then after a disturbance, it returns back to original equilibrium.
Lift and drag are created by the {{c1::pressure distribution}} over the wing.
[latex]$\mathbf{C}_{R}$[/latex] is the dimensionless {{c1::resultant (total)}} aerodynamic force vector
[$]C_{N}[/$] and [$]C_{T}[/$] are the components of [$]\mathbf{C}_{R}[/$] normal respectively tangential to the {{c1::body axis (the chordline)}}.
[$]C_{L}[/$] and [$]C_{D}[/$] are the components of [$]\mathbf{C}_{R}[/$] normal respectively tangential to the {{c1::freestream airflow}}.
All aerodynamic force vectors are made dimensionless (normalized) by dividing by:
The air flows over the wing, at varying speed, creating {{c1::lower}} pressure on the {{c2::upper}} side and {{c1::higher}} pressure on the {{c2::lower}} side.
The {{c2::moment coefficient [$$]C_{m}[/$$]}} of a wing is {{c1:: [$$] =\frac{M}{\frac{1}{2} \rho V^{2} S \bar{c} } [/$$] }}

In the aerodynamic forces acting on a wing, the normal force coefficient [$]C_N[/$] is related to the lift and drag coefficients [$]C_L, C_D[/$] by:
[$]C_{N}[/$] = [$]C_{L}[/$] {{c1::[$]\cos \alpha[/$]}} [$]+[/$] [$]C_{D}[/$] {{c1::[$]\sin \alpha[/$]}}

In the aerodynamic forces acting on a wing, the tangential force coefficient [$]C_T[/$] is related to the lift and drag coefficients [$]C_L, C_D[/$] by:
[$]C_{T}[/$] = [$]C_{D}[/$] {{c1::[$]\cos \alpha[/$]}} [$]-[/$] [$]C_{L}[/$] {{c1::[$]\sin \alpha[/$]}}
According to the small angle approximation, [$]\cos{\alpha} \approxeq[/$]... {{c1::[$]1[/$]}}
Applying the small angle approximation to the aerodynamic forces (lift, drag, normal, tangential) over a wing, [$]C_{N}= C_{L}[/$] {{c1::[$]\cdot 1[/$]}} [$]+ C_{D}[/$] {{c1::[$]\cdot \alpha[/$]}}
Applying the small angle approximation to the aerodynamic forces (lift, drag, normal, tangential) over a wing, [$]C_{T}= C_{D}[/$] {{c1::[$]\cdot 1[/$]}} [$] - C_{L}[/$] {{c1::[$]\cdot \alpha[/$]}}
At small angles, does [$]C_N \approxeq C_L[/$]?
Yes, because [$]C_{N}=C_{L}+C_{D} \alpha[/$] and both [$]C_D[/$] and [$]\alpha[/$] are small relative to [$]C_L[/$].
At small angles, does [$]C_T \approxeq C_D[/$]?
No, because [$]C_{T}=C_{D}-C_{L} \alpha[/$] and even though [$]\alpha[/$] is small, [$]C_L[/$] is large relative to [$]C_D[/$].
In the expression for the moment coefficient of a wing [$]C_{m}=\frac{M}{\frac{1}{2} \rho V^{2} S \bar{c} }[/$], what does does [$]\bar{c}[/$] represent?
The mean aerodynamic chord or average chord length of the wing, also known as mac.
What is the expression for dynamic pressure [$]q[/$]?
Which direction is the positive moment convention on a wing? (nose up or nose down)
Nose up is positive (clockwise by convention)
The {{c1::center of pressure}} on a wing is a point on the {{c2::mean aerodynamic chord}} where the {{c3::moment coefficient}} is zero.
[$]C_{m_{0}}[/$] is the moment coefficient around the {{c2::leading edge of the mac (or lemac)::point}} when {{c1::[$]C_N = 0[/$]::condition}}
The moment coefficient varies {{c1::linearly::somehow}} with the {{c2::angle of attack}} for {{c3::[$]\alpha < 10 \deg[/$]}}
The x-distance {{c1::[$]x_d - x_0[/$]}} along the mac  between the {{c1::lemac [$]x_0[/$]}} and the {{c1::center of pressure [$]x_d[/$]}} is also represented with {{c2::[$]e[/$]::symbol}}.

The location along the {{c4::mac (the x-axis of a wing)}} of the {{c4::center of pressure}} is given by:

{{c1::[$]\frac{e}{\bar{c} } =[/$] }}  {{c2::[$] = -\frac{C_{m_{0} } }{C_{N} }[/$] }} {{c3::[$]-\frac{d C_{m_{\left(x_{0}, z_{0}\right) } } }{d C_{N} }[/$] }}
At {{c1::positive}} angles of attack, [$]C_T[/$] becomes {{c2::negative}} because the {{c3::low pressure zone slightly above the leading edge sucks the wing forward instead of dragging it backward}}.
{{c1::Increasing::changing somehow}} the angle of attack [$]\alpha[/$] {{c2::increases::changing somehow}} the normal force coefficient [$]C_N[/$].

As the angle of attack [$]\alpha[/$] increases, the magnitude of the resultant force coefficient[$]\mathbf{C}_R[/$] {{c1::increases::changes somehow}} and its line of action moves {{c2::closer to::closer or farther}} the {{c3::center of pressure}}.

As the angle of attack [$]\alpha[/$] decreases, the magnitude of the resultant force coefficient[$]\mathbf{C}_R[/$] {{c1::decreases::changes somehow}} and its line of action moves {{c2::farther from::closer or farther}} the {{c3::center of pressure}}.
Why does the location of the center of pressure vary with the angle of attack [$]\alpha[/$]?
Because the line of action of the resultant force coefficient [$]\mathbf{C}_R[/$] moves along the mac.
The {{c1::aerodynamic center (ac)}} is the moment reference point about which the moment {{c2::does not::does/doesn't}} vary with angle of attack.
Does the location of the aerodynamic center (ac) vary with the angle of attack?
No, it is a fixed, single reference point.
The {{c1::angle of attack [$]\alpha[/$]}} is the angle between the {{c2::freestream airflow}} and the {{c2::body axis/chordline}}.
According to the small angle approximation, [$]\sin{\alpha} \approxeq[/$] {{c1::[$]\alpha[/$]}}
